# encode categorical data (Although I think decision tree can handle unencoded categorical data?)
df_encoded = pd.DataFrame()
for col in set(df.columns) - {'class'}:
    df_encoded[col] = df[col].astype('category').cat.codes
In [6]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split

# Split into training and testing groups, then encode binary class variable
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(df_encoded, 
                                                    df['class'], 
                                                    test_size=0.2, 
                                                    random_state=0,
                                                    shuffle=True
                                                   )

y_train = y_train.apply(lambda x: 1 if x == "b'p'" else 0)
y_test = y_test.apply(lambda x: 1 if x == "b'p'" else 0)
In [7]:
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV
from scipy.stats import randint

param_dist = {
    'max_depth': [None] + list(randint(1, 10).rvs(10)),
    'max_features': randint(1, 10),
    'min_samples_split': randint(2, 20),
    'min_samples_leaf': randint(1, 20),
}

rs_tree = RandomizedSearchCV(
    estimator=DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini', splitter='best'),
    param_distributions=param_dist,
    cv=3,
    n_iter=20,
    scoring='accuracy'
)

rs_tree.fit(X_train, y_train)
